'''''Children of the Jedi''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] bestselling novel written by [[Barbara Hambly]] and published by [[Bantam Spectra]] in [[April]] [[1995]]. The novel is set several months after [[Star Wars: The Jedi Academy Trilogy|''The Jedi Academy Trilogy'']]. It is the first volume of an informal [[Callista trilogy|trilogy]] involving ex&ndash;[[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Callista Ming]]. The next book in the cycle is [[Darksaber (novel)|''Darksaber'']] (1995) by [[Kevin J. Anderson]], followed by ''[[Planet of Twilight]]'' ([[1997]]), also written by Hambly. 

An [[Children of the Jedi (abridged audiobook)|audio version]] narrated by [[Anthony Heald]] was released in 2007.

==Publisher's summary==
===Hardcover===
''[[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Princess Leia]], [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]], and [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]] set out on a mission vital to the survival of the fragile [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]]. They are searching for the long-lost children of the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]], a quest that takes them to the once vibrant stronghold of [[Belsavis/Legends|Belsavis]]&mdash;a nearly forgotten frozen world. Leia has heard tales of a Jedi exodus from the dark crypts below the [[Planet/Legends|planet's]] surface. She has also heard that since the time of the exodus no one entering the crypts has returned alive.''

''Halfway across [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]], [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] has undertaken an equally dangerous expedition that, if it fails, could have fatal consequences for Leia, Han, and Chewbacca. Haunted by ominous dreams and guided by a force he cannot identify, Luke journeys to a remote [[Asteroid/Legends|asteroid]] field over the planet [[Pzob/Legends|Pzob]]. There he discovers the automated [[Dreadnought|Dreadnaught]] ''[[Eye of Palpatine]]''&mdash;from the [[Clone Wars/Legends|days of all-out war]]''.

''Camouflaged deep within a nebulous gas cloud and dormant for thirty years, ''Eye of Palpatine'' is governed by a super-sophisticated [[Artificial intelligence/Legends|artificial intelligence]] system known as [[the Will]]. Taken aboard the Dreadnaught, Luke is counseled by the [[Force ghost/Legends|spirit]] of [[Callista Ming|Callista]], a [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] who gave her life to stop the ship once before. Now Luke must learn from her how to destroy it once and for all. The Will has awakened. The ''Eye of Palpatine'' is on the move. Its mission: the total annihilation of Belsavis.''

''The mystery of the crypts, the invincible power of the Will, the lost Jedi, and the burgeoning passion between Luke and Callista come together in the stunning climax of ''Children of the Jedi''&mdash;the latest chapter in the magnificent ''Star Wars'' saga.''

===Paperback===
'''The chronicle of the dazzling universe of [[George Lucas]]'s blockbuster ''[[Star Wars]]'' films soars to new heights as the Republic faces its greatest challenge yet in&hellip;'''

'''''Children of the Jedi'''''

''Princess Leia, Han Solo, and Chewbacca set out on a mission vital to the survival of the fragile New Republic. They are searching for the long-lost children of the Jedi on the frozen world of Belsavis, from whose dark crypts no one has returned alive. Halfway across the galaxy, Luke Skywalker is on an equally dangerous mission. Taken aboard the enemy Dreadnaught ''Eye of Palpatine'', Luke must find a way to destroy the automated ship before it completes the mission encoded into its super-sophisticated artificial intelligence system: the total annihilation of Belsavis. To succeed, Luke will need the help of the spirit of the Jedi Knight Callista, who gave her life to stop the ship once before. The mystery of the crypts, the invincible power of the Dreadnaught, the lost Jedi, and the burgeoning passion between Luke and Callista come together in a stunning climax worthy of the magnificent ''Star Wars'' saga.''

==Plot summary==
Eight years after the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|Battle of Endor]], [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Princess Leia]], her family, and several other [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] representatives visit [[Ithor/Legends|Ithor]] to attend the [[Herd Meet/Legends|Time of Meeting]], an event that occurs once every three [[Standard year/Legends|years]]. During the event, they are accosted by [[Drub McKumb]], an old acquaintance of [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] who appears to have gone insane. From his mad ravings, they learn about the [[Children of the Jedi]] and the planet where they were hidden, [[Belsavis/Legends|Belsavis]]. Along with [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] are two of his new students, [[Cray Mingla]] and [[Nichos Marr/Legends|Nichos Marr]], who were part of the Children. While exploring Nichos' mind for more information, Luke uncovers coordinates leading to the [[Moonflower Nebula/Legends|Moonflower Nebula]]. The trio, accompanied by [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]], decide to explore these coordinates while Leia, Han, [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]] and [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]] head to Belsavis.

During the exploration of the Moonflower Nebula, the ship loaned to Luke, the ''[[Huntbird]]'', is attacked by plasma bolts from what appears to be an asteroid base hidden deep in the nebula. This asteroid turns out to be the automated [[Dreadnaught/Legends|Dreadnaught]] ''[[Eye of Palpatine]]'', one of the Galactic Empire's first functional [[Superweapon/Legends|superweapons]]. Forced to crash-land on [[Pzob/Legends|Pzob]], a primitive planet colonized by [[Gamorrean/Legends|Gamorreans]], the group meets [[Triv Pothman]], a former Stormtrooper stranded since [[18 BBY/Legends|18 BBY]]. They become embroiled into the conflict between the rival Gamorrean tribes [[Klagg tribe|Klagg]] and [[Gakfedd tribe|Gakfedd]] before being captured and brainwashed into believing they are Imperial stormtroopers by the ''Eye''. Luke discovers that the Dreadnaught, reactivated after being stopped 30 years earlier by Jedi [[Callista Ming|Callista Masana]] and [[Geith Eris]], was designed to destroy the Children of the Jedi. On the way, the ship's artificial intelligence, [[The Will]] picks up sentient beings from various species, including [[Talz/Legends|Talz]], [[Affytechan]]s, [[Jawa/Legends|Jawas]], [[Kitonak/Legends|Kitonaks]], [[Tusken Raider/Legends|Tusken Raiders]], [[Tripod]]s, and Gamorreans. Luke must now find a way to stop the Will and save all the kidnapped beings. He will encounter Callista whose spirit has been trapped in the ship's data banks since her ill-fated mission and the two quickly develop a close relationship.

Meanwhile, Han Solo and Princess Leia investigate the fate of the Children of the Jedi in the domed community of [[Plett's Well|Plawal]]. They uncovers a vast tunnel network and a [[Ismaren plot|conspiracy]] led by former [[Emperor's Hand/Legends|Emperor's Hand]] [[Roganda Ismaren/Legends|Roganda Ismaren]], who plans to establish her son [[Irek Ismaren|Irek]] as the new Emperor. Irek, who had a [[subelectronic converter]] installed into his brain, can use it to control [[Droid/Legends|droids]] and [[Computer/Legends|computers]] through [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. Roganda's plan involves using Irek's abilities to control the ''Eye of Palpatine'' to impress the powerful lords of the [[Juvex sector/Legends|Juvex]] and [[Senex sector/Legends|Senex]] sectors and use the superweapon as well as their wealth and influence to turn the tides of the civil war.

However, the plot is foiled when Luke, Cray, Nichos, and Callista manage to destroy the Dreadnaught, resulting in the deaths of Nichos and Cray. In the end, Callista's spirit is revived in Cray's body, as Cray, not wishing to live without Nichos, willingly relinquishes it.

==Development==
Callista Ming was originally intended to be "the great love of Luke Skywalker's life," as part of an assignment from [[Lucasfilm]] to author Barbara Hambly. However, fan reaction over the character Mara Jade from the [[Star Wars: The Thrawn Trilogy|''Thrawn Trilogy'']] had become such that Lucasfilm decided that Skywalker and Jade would ultimately end up together.<ref name=":0">[[Wookieepedia:Interview/Kevin J. Anderson|Interview with Kevin J. Anderson]]</ref> As such, Anderson worked with Hambly to find a way to slowly write Ming out over the course of the next novels, ''[[Darksaber (novel)|Darksaber]]'' and ''[[Planet of Twilight]]'', without killing off the character.<ref name=":0" />

==Continuity==
There is conflicting information on when the story takes place; Various statements within the text date it to [[11 ABY/Legends|11]], [[12 ABY/Legends|12]], and [[13 ABY/Legends|13 ABY]]. However, it is officially set in 12 ABY. It says Leia's is "not quite thirty," although in 12 ABY, she would be thirty-one years old.

The novel (along with [[Darksaber (novel)|''Darksaber'']]) states that the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] ended prior to the [[Great Jedi Purge]], and implies that [[Order 66/Legends|Order 66]] may not have been issued until after [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]] became [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Galactic Emperor]]. The [[prequel trilogy]] would not definitively establish this chronology for another ten years.

[[Dannik Jerriko]] is spelled "Danik Jericho," [[SoroSuub Corporation/Legends|SoroSuub]] is spelled "Sorosub," and "[[Seinar Corporation]]" was likely intended to be [[Santhe/Sienar Technologies]]. [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Thrawn]] was said to have been a [[High Admiral]], and the [[X-34 landspeeder/Legends|X-34]] landspeeder is called a ''T-70''. Furthermore, it's stated that Luke Skywalker destroyed the [[Sun Crusher]], when in fact it was [[Kyp Durron]], and that Luke felt the [[Destruction of Carida]] through [[The Force/Legends|the Force]], while in ''[[Champions of the Force]]'' he was unconscious at that time.

The character of [[Triv Pothman]] and the other [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] scheduled to be deployed aboard the ''[[Eye of Palpatine]]'' comes into conflict with the later [[Clone trooper/Legends|clone troopers]] of the prequel trilogy; however, they may be early non-clone recruits or [[GeNode]] clones.

Finally, there are issues with the description of the members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] as depicted here, specifically their decentralized structure and acceptance of family and relationship ties. Other than brief statements that [[Plett]] and [[Djinn Altis/Legends|Djinn Altis]] belonged to a "rogue" sect as mentioned in Callista's entry in ''[[The New Essential Guide to Characters]]'', this issue has been retconned in Karen Traviss's ''[[The Clone Wars: No Prisoners]]'', which details this rogue sect in full.

==Legacy==
Callista Ming would make subsequent appearances in [[Karen Traviss]]' novels ''[[Order 66: A Republic Commando Novel]] and [[The Clone Wars: No Prisoners]]''. The character would also play a more important role in the [[Star Wars: Fate of the Jedi|Fate of the Jedi]] series.

The characters of Roganda and Irek Ismaren would make another appearance in the [[Star Wars: The New Jedi Order|''New Jedi Order'']] novel ''[[The New Jedi Order: Enemy Lines II: Rebel Stand]]''.

